📄 Step 6: Add Jenkinsfile to GitHub Repo

In your project root (same place as app.py):

📄 Jenkinsfile
pipeline {
    agent any

    environment {
        IMAGE_NAME = "python-app"
        DOCKER_HUB_USER = "your-dockerhub-username"
    }

    stages {
        stage('Clone') {
            steps {
                git branch: 'main',
                    url: 'https://github.com/your-username/your-repo.git'
            }
        }

        stage('Build Image') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker build -t $DOCKER_HUB_USER/$IMAGE_NAME:latest .'
            }
        }

        stage('Push to Hub') {
            steps {
                withCredentials([usernamePassword(
                    credentialsId: 'dockerhub-creds',
                    usernameVariable: 'DOCKER_USER',
                    passwordVariable: 'DOCKER_PASS'
                )]) {
                    sh '''
                    echo $DOCKER_PASS | docker login -u $DOCKER_USER --password-stdin
                    docker push $DOCKER_HUB_USER/$IMAGE_NAME:latest
                    '''
                }
            }
        }

        stage('Deploy') {
            steps {
                sh 'docker run -d -p 5000:5000 $DOCKER_HUB_USER/$IMAGE_NAME:latest'
            }
        }
    }
}

👉 Replace:

your-dockerhub-username
your-username
your-repo
🔐 Step 7: Add Docker Hub Credentials in Jenkins

Go to Jenkins:

👉 Manage Jenkins → Credentials → Global → Add Credentials

Fill:

Username → your Docker Hub username
Password → Docker access token
ID → dockerhub-creds ✅ (VERY IMPORTANT)
⚙️ Step 8: Create Pipeline Job
Click New Item
Enter name → docker-pipeline
Select → Pipeline
Click OK
Configure:

👉 Pipeline section:

Definition → Pipeline script from SCM
SCM → Git
Repo URL → your GitHub repo URL
Branch → main

Click Save

